<br>
1)<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Make sure you are putting your art in the appropriate forum.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
I've been seeing waaaaaaay too many sketches in the completed black&amp;white art forum. This detracts from the folks who busted their humps to finish a piece.<br>
<br>
If you are unclear about what is finished and what is a sketch I'll demonstrate:<br>
a) finished:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm13.showMessage?topicID=908.topic">pub25.ezboard.com/fpolyka...=908.topic</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
there is adequate shading, a background,and some perspective. Even though it's still pencils it's more or less a finished piece.<br>
<br>
b)sketch:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm23.showMessage?topicID=113.topic">pub25.ezboard.com/fpolyka...=113.topic</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
Looks great! but it's not a finished piece, right? so this is what goes in the &quot;Art in Progress&quot; forum.<br>
<br>
2)<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  No more Notepad sketches</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
If you are posting work for critique it's because you spent time, thought and energy on the piece. Not because you were bored in class. Be respectful of others who are trying to get prepared art critiqued. If you drew something in class that you are really proud of..take the time to transfer it to some real media before posting it.<br>
<br>
3)<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Selective Critiquing</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
No one person can critique everything so by applying a little methodology to our madness we can make everyone happy. When you jump into a forum for Critique. Pick the thread with the lowest amount of replies. If you see a thread with 15 replies..chances are the artist has a good idea of the general opinion. If we select the lowest reply thread we begin to average out a solid 5 or 6 replies per thread and that's perfect. Everybody plays, everybody wins.<br>
<br>
4)<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Getting more Critiques</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Avoid the over-used post title &quot;C&amp;C please&quot; or &quot;Come in and C&amp;C&quot;..it's in the critiques forum. Everybody knows it's for C&amp;C..no need to advertise. Instead, just title the post what it is...if it's a dude on a snowboard, say, &quot;Dude on a Snowboard&quot;. <br>
<br>
Don't title it &quot;Gee, I suck&quot; either. <br>
<br>
Also, expand your repetoire a bit. There's a whole mess of headshots out there for C&amp;C. If it's a problem with heads you are working on specifically then OK. But otherwise you should be trying action, multiple views, sequentials, backgrounds, vehicles, landscapes...ect. The only way to really improve quickly is to leave your artistic comfort zones and push your skills. Just like weight-lifting. <br>
<br>
More weight + more repititions = more muscle.<br>
New techniques + more attempts = greater skills<br>
<br>
Good luck and Have fun out there!<br>
